===Etymology===
From {{der|en|enm|waste}}, {{m|enm|wast||stature, waist}}, from {{der|en|ang|*wǣst}}, {{m|ang|*wǣxt}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*wahstuz||growth, development, stature, build}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂weg-|*h₂weg-s-|to multiply, increase}}. Cognate with {{cog|gmh|wahst||growth}}, {{cog|da|vækst||growth}}, {{cog|sv|växt||growth, development, size}}, {{cog|is|vöxtur||growth}}, {{cog|got|𐍅𐌰𐌷𐍃𐍄𐌿𐍃||growth}}. Related to {{cog|ang|weaxan||to grow, increase}}. More at {{l|en|wax}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/weɪst/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪst|lang=en}}
* Homophones: [[waste]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The [[part]] of the [[body]] [[between]] the [[pelvis]] and the [[stomach]].
# A part of a [[piece]] of [[clothing]] that covers the waist.
# The [[narrow]] [[connection]] between the [[thorax]] and [[abdomen]] in certain [[insect]]s (e.g., [[bee]]s, [[ant]]s and [[wasp]]s).
# The middle portion of the [[hull]] of a [[ship]] or the [[fuselage]] of an [[aircraft]].
# {{lb|en|nautical}} That part of the upper deck of a ship between the [[quarterdeck]] and the [[forecastle]].
#* '''1851''', [[w:Herman Melville|Herman Melville]], ''[[w:Moby Dick|Moby Dick]]'', [[s:Moby-Dick/Chapter 18|chapter 18]]
#*: There he stood, very quietly overlooking some sailmakers who were mending a top-sail in the '''waist'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The middle part of anything.
#: {{rfquotek|Shakespeare}} <!--who used it for the middle of a musical instrument, and of a period of time-->

